&lt;p&gt;Immigrant communities in America have grown cohesive and sometimes even powerful by organizing themselves into civically aware and politically active diasporas. But for immigrants from Central Asia, one of the youngest communities in the United States, growing numbers have yielded little in the way of political cohesion.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Some 350,000 immigrants have arrived from these former Soviet countries since the 1950s. The largest group, Uzbeks, is scattered from Key West, Florida, to Anchorage, Alaska, with estimated numbers at 250,000 strong. Brooklyn, New York, has become a self-contained Little Uzbekistan, centered on the Brighton Beach neighborhood: colorful stores and restaurants, supermarkets and bakeries abound.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Yet these new Americans citizens and Green Card holders remain atomized and politically passive, focused mostly within their communities rather than on civic debates and public responsibilities.&lt;/p&gt;
